00:17:51.400 --> 00:17:59.400
Now it seems clear that the further back in time we travel, the closer we get to the original words of truth.

00:17:59.400 --> 00:18:03.400
But there is one more stop that we do not want to miss.

00:18:03.400 --> 00:18:11.400
So we've come to the John Rylands Library in Manchester, known locally as the Cathedral of Books.

00:18:11.400 --> 00:18:31.740
This is Papyrus 52, dated by some scholars to around 125 CE.

00:18:31.740 --> 00:18:36.740
It's a fragment of the oldest copy of John.

00:18:36.740 --> 00:18:43.740
In fact, it's the oldest fragment of the Christian Greek scriptures that has ever been found.

00:18:44.740 --> 00:18:51.859
What does it contain? Another simple yet profound sentence.

00:18:51.859 --> 00:19:03.789
For this I have been born and for this I have come into the world that I should bear witness to the truth.

00:19:03.789 --> 00:19:09.789
